@zou3519 is right. More concretely, right now we preemptively guard on `requires_grad` of tensors, as part of the `TensorCheck` guard (which also preemptively guard on other properties like dispatch key, etc.): 
https://github.com/pytorch/pytorch/blob/3849fd13de1a5ee727fd64351edb0d3b1bb637a9/torch/csrc/dynamo/guards.cpp#L207-L213

But in theory, we only need to guard on a property if the compilation specialized its behavior based on the property. In this case it's either:
1. User code directly uses the `requires_grad` attribute, e.g., to do conditional branch, which affects the code path Dynamo is tracing.
2. AOTDispatcher uses it for AOTAutograd (it stays faithful to `torch.no_grad` as well) or some other C++ PyTorch code, which affects the output of the forward and backward graphs.

In this issue, the preemptive guard basically diverged from what (2) would've guarded on, given its knowledge and usage of `requires_grad` and `torch.no_grad`. So to fix this properly, I think we'd need to remove the `requires_grad` check from `TensorCheck` guard, and lazily emit `requires_grad` check during (2) to resolve this issue, and during (1) to preserve complete soundness. This will also fix #139476, but similarly could also increase guard latency.

